<sub>FP</sub> curve of the model neuron&#x0201d; in Materials and Methods for details). According to bifurcation theory, this implies that the fixed point of the dynamics of the fast subsystem can be destabilized as <italic>b</italic> decreases only via a Hopf bifurcation (a bifurcation where a limit cycle emerges) [<xref rid="pcbi-0030156-b018" ref-type="bibr">18</xref>,<xref rid="pcbi-0030156-b019" ref-type="bibr">19</xref>]. Whether the bifurcation actually occurs and the value, <italic>b</italic>
<sub>Hopf</sub>, where it occurs, depend on <italic>I</italic>
<sub>app</sub> (<italic>b</italic>
<sub>Hopf</sub> = 0.18 for the parameters of <xref ref-type="fig" rid="pcbi-0030156-g005">Figure 5</xref>A&#x02013;<xref ref-type="fig" rid="pcbi-0030156-g005">5</xref>C). As depicted in <xref ref-type="fig" rid="pcbi-0030156-g005">Figure 5</xref>A, the limit cycle that emerges at <italic>b</italic> = <italic>b</italic>
